content.description:
Interesting and progressively diffcult climbing up overhanging rock transitions into a long section of fabulous slab climbing (5.7) to anchors just below the large hanging garden.

Named for the active allergen in poison oak which was quite heavy at the base of the route and even partway up the rock face.
content.protection:
6 bolts, ring anchors

Bolts are 3/8" with a 1/2" bolt at the crux.
content.location:
Located 20 feet right of

Super Soul Slab

.

content.description:
Start just left of the arete at an obvious shot hole.

Make a couple of tricky moves and then move quickly to the black bulge.   The crux is passing the 3rd bolt to get established above the bulge.

Easy moves follow to the anchors.
content.protection:
4 bolts, anchored shared by

The Natural
content.location: The route follows the prominent arete on the obvious wall in the lower falls area. This route takes the left side of the arete.

content.description: The crux is down low getting from the 1st bolt to the 2nd bolt, an intricate 5 feet of climbing that may have you baffled or put a large smile on your face. This is a good warm up before doing something a little longer, such as Eco Challenge.
content.protection: 3 bolts to cold shuts
content.location: Starts on pink granite up a blank looking face (look close they are there) Once you get past the 2nd bolt it is large chunky holds to the top.

content.description: Thin technical climbing on overhanging face.
content.protection: 6 bolts, sport anchor
content.location: Furthest right route on the left (north) side of the canyon, just left of the waterfall approach.

climbs.name: Super Soul Slab
climbs.fa: Matt Myers, P.2 FFA Aaron lawrence. P.3 FFA Carlos Baron

content.description:
A very fun climb and great for practicing your slab skills. Start at the base of the slab to the right of Eco-challenge area. This is a Slab climb so stay away from the chossy corner.

P.1 5.7 Steep start to high quality slab with a tricky bulge up high, staying right is recommended 100' 9 bolts Chain anchor.

P.2 5.8 Fun slab to high quality face with several different options, Take a right at the top to a comfy belay ledge with two 2 bolt anchors. 8 bolts 60'. You can link P.1 and P.2 for 155' of fun, 19 draws.

P.3 5.9 Climb the face just right of the arching dihedral, head strait up at the end with a crux finale. 50' 9 bolts, bolted anchor. Anchors to the right belong to BFF and LOL, 100' to the middle tier belay anchors. A rope stretcher so be safe.

At the P.3 Anchor, a great option is to clip and pass the anchor to a big belay ledge with a two bolt anchor. Continue on I Cant Remember or Call it what you want. The fixed line that leads to sidewalk ledge so there are lots of link up options.
content.protection: Fully bolted, can be enjoyed with a 60m Rope and 10 Quick Draws.
content.location:
The long slab to the right of the

Eco Challenge

area.

climbs.name: Summer Rain
climbs.fa: Equipped by Brent Webster, FA: Jason Milford 7/2017

content.description: Start just right of a seepage. Pull a hard undercling move to get off the ground. Four bolts of difficult thin climbing leads to a dihedral. Finish up on an airy arete.
content.protection: 10 bolts to steel biners
content.location: Just left of swamp thing.

content.description: Some balancey moves lead to a good sized edge and easier climbing.  Traverse right through loose blocks.
content.protection: Micro gear (1 piece or if you're lucky, two) and tree limb sling
content.location: Rap from Frankincense anchors.

content.description: Climb well-featured pink and grey granite into a flared corner system at the second bolt, transition past a dark band of rock at the third bolt and finish up past nice holds on more pink/grey rock. Short but entertaining, and a good warm-up for the lower area.
content.protection: 3 bolts, shuts
content.location:
Located on a small face between

Three Kings

on the left and

Unnatural Act

on the right.

content.description: Start the slab then tackle the overhanging face, lots of glue reinforcement.
content.protection: 10 bolts, chain anchor
content.location:
Two routes right of

Eco Challenge

.

content.description: The crux is found getting off the ground and pulling the lip at the very top of the climb. The climb follow the arete to the right of Unnatural Act. There is a hidden bolt at the top. This is a fun route with some hidden holds and daring moves. A must if you are in the area.
content.protection: 6 bolts to cold shut, chain anchor
content.location: The route follows the prominenant arete on the obvious wall in the lower falls area. The short (45 ft.) wall can be seen from the highway.

content.description: The Bulge roof line.

Between

content.description: Fun short climb, the crux is at the 3rd bolt and getting past it. Once you mantel the first face watch out for the Yucca bush its out for blood. If you choose to do this route bring your best belay the rope seems to be in the way of your fall line and needs to move as you do.
content.protection: 5 bolts, anchors w/ chains at the top

climbs.name: Maniac McGee
climbs.fa: FA Jon Lindquist. Route was developed by Brent Webster and Upper pitch also by Matt Myers

content.description:
2 pitch route starting to the right of The Natural and left of Eco Challenge.

P1.10a. 12 bolts. Start in the dihedral up few bolts, clip the perm draw and ride the arête up to some brown anchors.

P2.11b 13 bolts. Go up some easy terrain and slightly left aiming for the huge boulder looking arête, clip the perm draw and crux your way up the tricky yet amazing arête.

120 feet total if link the pitches. 25 quickdraws and couple more for anchors. 80 meter rope mandatory unless you break it down to 2 pitches.

The upper arête is named the Machete Arete
content.protection: 25 bolts and a few perm draws
content.location: To the right of The Natural and left of Eco Challenge. Start in the dihedral.

content.description: This route continues up from the anchors of "King Under the Mountain" through somewhat ledgy terrain with interesting cruxes between good rests.  The true crux of the route comes as you are pulling over a steep block and have to cut feet and mantle above.  You could climb this as a second pitch, but most people will just combine the two sections into one long pitch.  If you climb this one with a 60m rope, make sure you have a knot in the end of the rope and be ready to untie and downclimb the last few feet of the route as a 60 won't quite reach the ground.
content.protection: bolts, most of which have permadraws on them
content.location: Continue up from the anchors of "King Under the Mountain".

content.description: Fun route easy beginning the crux is in the middle where it smooths out a little and the hands are up high and to the left. The roof is fun and offers just a little exposure. Perfect climb for beginners. Look out for the tree branches when you rap off.
content.protection: Small nuts and cams (1/2" to 2"), 2 bolts with rings at the top.
content.location: Once down in the Lower Falls area look to your left (west) you will see a large oak tree. the climb is under the oak tree (think ALL day shade) The route follows the obvious crack to the roof in the middle of the formation. there is a bolted sport route just to the right (east)

content.description:
Starts right of super soul slab. And left of urishiol.

Once on slab bear left heading up vertical wall, to first ledge, continuing above is 11a.
content.protection: 15 bolts, and 2 chains with mussies

climbs.name: The Fourth Wise Man
climbs.fa: FFA Sam Schmetzer, FA Matt Myers. 9-28-2012

content.description: Start by steming in the corner then commit to the face staying left of the bolts and finish up to the anchors. Still a little dirty so be careful.
content.protection: Sewn up with 6 bolts, chain anchor.
content.location: The almond colored hangers left of Three Kings.

content.description: This is a fun route that starts off with some easy 5.8 climbing through the first 4 bolts, the crux is then encountered as you make some balancy moves between the fifth and sixth bolts.  After the sixth bolt, the climbing eases up until one final V1 boulder problem between the last bolt and the anchors.
content.protection: 8 bolts to 2 bolt anchor with mussy hooks
content.location:
Just right of

Rabble Rouser

.

climbs.name: Eco Challenge
climbs.fa: (TR) Aaron Rough & Chris Miller, 1997, FL: Aaron Rough, 1997

content.description: This is a rather long climb. It starts in a prominent corner just right of cool looking arete. The starts is in loose corner and makes its way out onto the face. Once you get to the first bolt the rock solidifies. This is where the bat with the huge fangs was chillin right on a key hand hold. The bats do not normally nest on this climb, I think that this bat was sick. Toward the top it goes past vertical a few degrees but the holds are solid, you just gotta find them since there really isn't any chalk marks.
content.protection: 8 bolts, closed cold shuts at the top

climbs.name: Centers for dihedral control (C.D.C.) "aka fire crotch"

content.description:
Crux is the 3 move boulder problem to establish the dihedral.

You can A0 bolt to bolt, through this section using the four available bolts.

If free climbing use second and forth, of the four available bolts.
content.protection: 13 bolts, and chains
content.location: Route starts right of urishiol, and left of what used to be swamp thing. Look for the prominent dihedral where a 30' tall 20' wide curtain of poison oak once was.

content.description:
This super fun route takes a beautiful position on the cliff as it wanders upwards. Fully bolted, no trad gear necessary!

P1. 5.7. 9 Bolts, Chain Anchor, 90 feet. Start by climbing Rumble in the Rubble Clip the Rumble anchor with a quickdraw and continue up past bolts and a permadraw up to the Anchor on a shared  belay ledge with Eco Challenge.

P.2. 5.8. 11 Bolts, Chain Anchors, 90 feet. Climb up the beautiful slab tending right staying close to and sometimes on the arête. About 2/3 up traverse right passing the arête and head into the corner, then up the block to finish on the Sniper Ledge.

(P.1 & P.2 can be combined for a 180 pitch. You can retreat by two 100 rappels)

WARNING: Pitches 3 and 4 have been completely removed due to loose rock. Bolts and anchors have been taken out. Please do not climb.
content.protection: Fully bolted, Chain anchors. Can be done with 12 quickdraws and a 60m rope!
content.location:
Start by climbing

Rumble in the Rubble

.

content.description: Start at ground level and work your way up the flakes left to vertical crack.  Then step right and follow intuitive line up right corner on surprisingly fun holds.  Overall fun route for beginners and veterans alike.
content.protection: 0.5-2" cams. No direct top anchors, but you can use Frankincense top anchor with a directional cam (BD #2) at top of route.
content.location: Route starts under large oak tree in left upgoing slot to the left of Frankincense.
